00:18:36.030 --> 00:18:39.810
a problem presenting
accessible content to our users

00:18:39.810 --> 00:18:41.030
if we use these overlays."

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:46.740
We have not used any overlays,
we don't want to because we want

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:49.330
to do accessibility the right way.

00:18:49.330 --> 00:18:54.390
That is actually not by
adding glue or extra content.

00:18:56.890 --> 00:18:57.240
Test?

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:58.980
>> ANNA: Test.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:19:01.960
We worked really hard on
this page where you got

00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:05.300
every technical back-end
stuff put together

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:10.640
with all the front-end
content and design as well.

00:19:10.640 --> 00:19:14.000
We went to the part where
we actually wanted to test

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.760
and test even though we had a really
short period of time to do this,

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:22.100
it was a big priority for us because
we think users are very important.

00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:27.300
We started with the
in-house with all the teams

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:30.430
with all our colleagues,
they got the site and they came

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:34.070
with their views and their inputs
first in the first edition,

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:38.860
then we wanted to get the point
of view of our target groups.

00:19:38.860 --> 00:19:43.040
We did a qualitative study where
we interviewed different people

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:44.530
from our target group.

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:48.740
We did the approach that
was think out loud tests,

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:53.340
which meant that we sat with users
and users got different tasks

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:57.720
to solve and while doing so they
were supposed to think out loud

00:19:57.720 --> 00:20:01.410
what they met and what happened
so we could get an understanding

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:05.270
of how they were thinking
while following these tasks.

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:10.190
This was also combined with
a lot of questionnaires

00:20:10.190 --> 00:20:11.960
to the different groups.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:16.740
This mass together was the
testing kit, and I want to stress

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:19.760
that we can,
of course not generalize anything.

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.310
I think that the testing
we had was about 25.

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:27.090
We can only say what this person
did and why he or her did it,

00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:31.330
but it still gave us very many
insights to different things.

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:40.860
When we did the design of this
webpage, we did from the beginning,

00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:45.570
have a lot of focus on alternative
ways to get information, of course.

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:51.790
We wanted to keep it as Ole was
saying, very clean and very simple,

00:20:51.790 --> 00:20:53.940
easy to overcome.

00:20:53.940 --> 00:20:56.790
You saw the old one,
it was very cluttered.

00:20:56.790 --> 00:21:01.050
We of course had a lot of focus
on our contrast and colors,

00:21:01.050 --> 00:21:04.710
but even though we are the institute,
we did want to have colors.

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:10.290
We wanted to be in line with
our identity, but of course,

00:21:10.290 --> 00:21:13.050
we wanted to reach a triple-A.

00:21:15.670 --> 00:21:18.920
We did a special design.

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:22.140
I actually put the picture here
on the slide, on the right.

00:21:22.140 --> 00:21:25.860
We have these main menus on the
front page, and they are basically

00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:28.010
with the picture and text.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:34.060
Then for the people with a vision
impairment, we changed their box

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:36.090
to this black with yellow writing.

00:21:37.670 --> 00:21:40.890
We did it of course,
also for the people with low vision,

00:21:40.890 --> 00:21:46.500
so it was easier to see, but a
lot of our users use so much zoom

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:48.170
that it wasn't primarily for them.

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:53.440
It was also a design decision
to give focus to our area,

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:55.710
so people with a vision
when they came in,

00:21:55.710 --> 00:21:59.510
they quickly could get the code,
that this is a special place

00:21:59.510 --> 00:22:01.020
and that we focus on vision.

00:22:02.310 --> 00:22:05.060
The yellow text on
black sent this message

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:08.470
that people here need some
specialized treatments.

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:13.600
We also hope to signal
that we are a place

00:22:13.600 --> 00:22:15.130
that knows very much about this.

00:22:16.510 --> 00:22:19.110
Another design thing we
did was that we wanted

00:22:19.110 --> 00:22:22.120
to keep all our content
in the center of the page.

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:27.280
The old website, we had a column to
the left center and to the right,

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:29.740
and it could at times
be very confusing.

00:22:29.740 --> 00:22:32.460
At this site, we really wanted
to keep it simple, to have it all

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:35.570
in one place, and going downward.

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:41.440
The last thing that I brought here
today to what we thought a lot

00:22:41.440 --> 00:22:46.640
about when designing this
was our topography and fund.

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:51.830
This is not part of the WCAG,
but a thing that we really say often,

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:54.860
it's very important to look upon.

00:22:54.860 --> 00:23:00.390
I have held talks about this
subject alone, and I'm not going

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:04.080
to get into that here, but I'll
just say that it's important

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:08.730
to have a focus on the characteristic
shapes, the large openings

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:11.990
in a font and that
it's a good space.

00:23:11.990 --> 00:23:19.520
As I put this picture of
different fonts, a word like 1

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:23.100
and Illinois is a good
word to test your typings

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:28.620
because it's usually very hard to see
the difference between the number 1,

00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:33.130
the large I, the small
L, and these words.

00:23:33.130 --> 00:23:38.140
This is a good tip for something
you can test when choosing your font

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:39.140
for your pages.

00:23:40.790 --> 00:23:47.380
This brings me to when we did
the testing, what did we change

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:48.720
in the design?

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:51.570
What did come to our intention?

00:23:51.570 --> 00:23:55.280
As Ole was into this with the
navigation, we of course had a lot

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:59.680
of ways to navigate the page,
but I think we got really, really--

00:24:01.020 --> 00:24:04.730
We just saw how important it
actually is with the navigation.

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:09.910
I expected,
and I know some screen users get in

00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:14.250
and they use the arrow down to
look at the page, but in this test,

00:24:14.250 --> 00:24:17.720
we could also see that they
went for the search field,

00:24:17.720 --> 00:24:20.480
or they immediately
opened the element list.

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:24.230
I had a picture of that here as
well in the NVDA screen reader

00:24:24.230 --> 00:24:28.290
where they get all the headings
and all the links immediately.

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:33.070
That shows the importance of
really writing some good link text

00:24:33.070 --> 00:24:34.070
and some good headings.

00:24:35.490 --> 00:24:38.670
They also went for
checking page titles.

00:24:38.670 --> 00:24:42.470
They found our button,
go to content, and they have a lot

00:24:42.470 --> 00:24:45.660
of different strategies to
access this page where people

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:48.520
with A vision did as expected.

00:24:48.520 --> 00:24:51.050
They went down, they looked,
and they found the main menus

00:24:51.050 --> 00:24:52.050
that we designed.

00:24:53.060 --> 00:24:55.780
It's very important
to have many ways in.

00:24:55.780 --> 00:25:02.560
The search field, I'd like to say
something about, almost everyone

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:07.900
that used the search field
that we-- One of the things

00:25:07.900 --> 00:25:10.190
that we discovered that we did
wrong, in the beginning,

00:25:10.190 --> 00:25:16.010
was that we actually did gather
our content in very long pages.

00:25:16.010 --> 00:25:20.690
We had this page for people with
visual impairment, and it turned out

00:25:20.690 --> 00:25:22.770
when they were searching
they got one hit,

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:24.860
which basically could
be a good thing.

00:25:24.860 --> 00:25:28.730
It's not a lot to be confused
with, but the pages were so long.

00:25:28.730 --> 00:25:31.030
When you were using a screen
reader, it was very difficult

00:25:31.030 --> 00:25:36.010
to find the content within that page,
whereas we could see that people

00:25:36.010 --> 00:25:39.620
with A vision had no
problems because the colors

00:25:39.620 --> 00:25:44.400
and the design made it easier
to find the different sections.

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:47.790
Actually, after testing,
we split up some pages again,

00:25:47.790 --> 00:25:51.630
so we got more pages and more
search results, but it's easier

00:25:51.630 --> 00:25:54.170
to access the different contents.

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:58.110
I still think all in all today,
I think we have had 65 pages

00:25:58.110 --> 00:26:01.480
on this side compared to
the old where we have 3000.

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:07.570
We still have focused
our content a lot.

00:26:07.570 --> 00:26:10.610
One more thing that
on this page we have,

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:14.280
we don't have very many
pictures and graphical objects,

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:17.420
but after testing,
we even had fewer on the sides

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:22.130
that were directly targeted
people who use assistive aids,

00:26:22.130 --> 00:26:24.460
so if it doesn't have any
meaning, we took it away

00:26:24.460 --> 00:26:26.500
so it doesn't make a lot of noise.

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:32.480
The last point where we
really changed the designs,

00:26:32.480 --> 00:26:38.000
and we will share that experience,
is that we saw that a lot

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.620
of the people got cornered
or stuck when they finished

00:26:42.620 --> 00:26:46.410
when it came down to the end of
a page and finished the content,

00:26:46.410 --> 00:26:47.770
where were they to go?

00:26:47.770 --> 00:26:52.080
We actually ended up designing a
lot of more go back to the main page

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:54.870
or didn't you find what
you were looking for?

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:55.870
Go here.

00:26:56.680 --> 00:27:00.510
In the end, I guess I put the
last picture on this slide,

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:06.300
we added that to the top with the
visual arrow up and showing its link.

00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:10.190
If you ended there,
you got back up again.

00:27:10.190 --> 00:27:14.800
Basically, we found more ways
to guide the user around.

00:27:17.210 --> 00:27:27.750
Then the content part of our website,
we did always have a big focus

00:27:27.750 --> 00:27:29.170
on easy language.

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:34.040
We have a very complex professional
language with a lot of long,

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:35.510
complex words.

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:40.860
Of course, we really focused on
making the language more accessible

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:42.480
and easy to read.

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:47.740
We also, all through, have a
very big focus on language use.

00:27:47.740 --> 00:27:50.760
We believe that you aren't your
handicap, but you have one.

00:27:52.270 --> 00:27:57.970
We make a big effort to
write people with a handicap

00:27:57.970 --> 00:28:03.610
and not handicapped
people, but after we tested

00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:07.400
with some different users,
we got more attention points,

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:10.840
and some of the testing we
did, and some of the task was

00:28:10.840 --> 00:28:17.740
to find some of the employment
offers we have for the target groups,

00:28:17.740 --> 00:28:20.890
but very quickly we could see
they got no hits when trying

00:28:20.890 --> 00:28:25.860
to find this in the search
field because this subject

00:28:25.860 --> 00:28:28.440
or area has so many
different names.

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:32.840
You can write job, profession,
it could be work, occupation,

00:28:32.840 --> 00:28:36.240
employment, and of
course, the person

00:28:36.240 --> 00:28:40.420
who was testing it didn't use
the same vocabulary as we did.

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:44.610
We get back and all the big areas,
we started using a lot of synonyms

00:28:44.610 --> 00:28:47.050
to find and get this
into the content.

00:28:48.250 --> 00:28:52.460
Then also, a thing we discovered
was with the page titles,

00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:57.780
and that how we editors sometimes
can get a bit too creative.

00:28:57.780 --> 00:29:03.540
We had a lot of videos, and podcasts
with a lot of good inspiration

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:05.930
and we thought we are going
to collect this in a page,

00:29:05.930 --> 00:29:07.800
and we called it Find Inspiration.

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:10.900
It's brilliant, but
testing, again, we saw

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:14.500
that the users didn't find anything
because they search on video,

00:29:14.500 --> 00:29:16.830
they search on
podcasts, and no hits.

00:29:17.850 --> 00:29:19.750
Being specific is another advice.

00:29:20.960 --> 00:29:22.960
Now we split it up and
we have a podcast side

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:28.460
and we have a video side and
the creativity side, we use it

00:29:28.460 --> 00:29:31.660
in other places.

00:29:31.660 --> 00:29:34.150
Then one more point
was that we spend a lot

00:29:34.150 --> 00:29:37.720
of time guiding our users
in the text, for example,

00:29:37.720 --> 00:29:43.490
we have this, contact our teams
and at the beginning of that page,

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:50.670
we make sure we have texts that
say the content here is written

00:29:50.670 --> 00:29:55.950
in alphabetical order in three
columns so that the user who use zoom

00:29:55.950 --> 00:30:01.330
or screen readers know how to search
for the information before starting.

00:30:02.830 --> 00:30:05.890
That is also some small things
we do to make it easier.

00:30:06.980 --> 00:30:11.120
In the end, I'm just going
to say that, make a checklist

00:30:11.120 --> 00:30:12.470
and give it to your editors.

00:30:13.810 --> 00:30:16.760
Even though we are many people
here, it's really easy

00:30:16.760 --> 00:30:20.290
that you forget a small thing,
alternative text, the headings,

00:30:20.290 --> 00:30:24.630
put it in right, and very slowly,
it gets all inaccessible again.

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:28.870
That was my last good advice.

00:30:28.870 --> 00:30:30.462
I think that was it for this slide.

00:30:30.462 --> 00:30:31.296
>> OLE: Yes.

00:30:32.780 --> 00:30:35.430
When we design for
screen reader users,

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:44.020
we're actually having some issues
always because screen reader users

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:45.500
are very complex.

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:49.980
There are different screen
readers that do different things

00:30:49.980 --> 00:30:52.110
in a different way.

00:30:52.110 --> 00:30:56.890
For instance, there is a very
much difference on how voiceover

00:30:56.890 --> 00:31:01.000
on the iPhone works compared to,
for instance, NVDA or SuperNova.

00:31:03.530 --> 00:31:08.680
One of the things when it
comes to that is more or less,

00:31:08.680 --> 00:31:13.040
even though they're different,
they comply to the same things.

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:17.000
There are some differences when
it comes to which area attributes

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:22.900
and so on, they conform to but more
or less they're okay, all of these.

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:29.610
Users have different levels of
experience and different ways

00:31:29.610 --> 00:31:30.980
of doing things.

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:34.186
The complexity here
might not actually be

00:31:34.187 --> 00:31:36.400
in the excessive technology,

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:41.660
but also in the users,
there are different veracity levels.

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:43.340
There are different languages.

00:31:43.340 --> 00:31:45.300
There are different voices.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:51.190
For instance, we have a Danish voice
that pronounces some words really,

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:52.360
really strange.

00:31:52.360 --> 00:31:56.430
You can actually hear on
some of our blind users

00:31:56.430 --> 00:31:58.890
which voice they're using.

00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:08.330
That's a complex issue,
not complex as it can't be solved

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:11.680
because there are actually some
very good guidelines when it comes

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:15.330
to accessibility for screen
reader users in the WCAG.

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:18.300
If you look there,
you don't have to be scared,

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:22.770
but some of the things
when it comes to the users

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:28.670
and the way they use the webpage
are where the problems can start.

00:32:28.670 --> 00:32:33.580
One of the things we found out was
we actually want to help our users.

00:32:33.580 --> 00:32:37.000
We made a guide for the
users of screen readers.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:40.940
That meant we tried to describe
how the pages were built,

00:32:40.940 --> 00:32:45.040
how are they marked up
when it comes to headings.

00:32:45.040 --> 00:32:47.140
Are there things
they are not used to?

00:32:47.140 --> 00:32:51.870
One of the things that some
of our users were not used

00:32:51.871 --> 00:32:53.590
to were accordions.

00:32:53.590 --> 00:32:56.670
We described how they
use these accordions,

00:32:56.671 --> 00:32:58.770
and what were their function.

00:32:58.770 --> 00:33:01.830
They were buttons,
maybe headings, and so on.

00:33:01.830 --> 00:33:05.930
They could be folded
in and out and so on.

00:33:05.930 --> 00:33:09.470
Giving the users some
guidance were key.

00:33:10.890 --> 00:33:15.110
One of the things that we actually
always discuss more or less is,

00:33:16.840 --> 00:33:21.490
is it a problem that we have
when it comes to accessibility.

00:33:21.490 --> 00:33:24.840
Is it a technical problem
or is it a user problem

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:28.290
because some of the
feedback we get is hard?

00:33:28.290 --> 00:33:32.580
For instance,
Anna mentioned the title attribute.

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:38.480
I think to the most part,
we actually have great titles,

00:33:38.480 --> 00:33:45.850
but what if the user actually wants
to read out the link for a page?

00:33:45.850 --> 00:33:51.490
Will that give the user some idea of
where the user is on this webpage?

00:33:51.490 --> 00:33:55.700
Not necessarily,
but we have users that try that.

00:33:55.700 --> 00:34:00.380
That is one of the things we can
say, how can we fix this?

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:01.710
Is it a user problem?

00:34:02.730 --> 00:34:06.000
Can we describe to the user
how we want them to interact

00:34:06.001 --> 00:34:07.090
with the webpage?

00:34:09.520 --> 00:34:12.690
Some of the issues we have
are actually user issues

00:34:12.690 --> 00:34:15.080
because using a
screen reader is hard.

00:34:15.080 --> 00:34:16.140
It is complex.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:24.960
When we test and when we do some
of the tests with screen readers,

00:34:24.960 --> 00:34:31.440
we keep our focus very
much upon the WCAG

00:34:31.440 --> 00:34:34.480
because are we perceiving
this correctly?

00:34:34.480 --> 00:34:36.910
Are we understanding this?

00:34:36.910 --> 00:34:39.490
Are we able to operate this?

00:34:39.490 --> 00:34:42.930
Are we able to have a
robust way to do this

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:50.950
because that is the technical
way we can catch this?

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:58.080
Some of the things that are actually
hard sometimes are understanding

00:34:59.450 --> 00:35:02.970
how things will be pronounced,
abbreviations, are they correct,

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:03.970
are they not?

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:12.000
Actually, some things are hard even
because we are a small language area.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:17.390
That means that, for instance,
if we want to have an English page,

00:35:17.390 --> 00:35:19.910
we have to make sure
it's marked up correctly.

00:35:21.410 --> 00:35:25.820
For us, we're not using something
like Polylang, multi-poly,

00:35:25.820 --> 00:35:30.490
I don't know right now but
we have an English template

00:35:30.490 --> 00:35:32.860
that marks up the
language in parts.

00:35:34.930 --> 00:35:41.270
The heading or the banner, the
navigation area will be in Danish.

00:35:41.270 --> 00:35:46.880
If the screen reader actually
understands how this markup is done,

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:48.520
it will be read out in Danish.

00:35:48.520 --> 00:35:52.650
When it comes to the English content,
it will switch to the English voice.

00:35:52.650 --> 00:36:00.290
That is, VK 311,312, that we are
actually trying to be aware of.

00:36:00.290 --> 00:36:03.480
That is actually one of the
things that are really hard

00:36:03.480 --> 00:36:07.990
when it comes to the difficulties
we're having that is the language.

00:36:10.210 --> 00:36:11.210
Yes, time's running.

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:16.410
Low vision users, we test,
of course, when it comes to them,

00:36:16.410 --> 00:36:18.850
and that is actually really
hard because people use

00:36:18.850 --> 00:36:20.430
different magnifications.

00:36:20.430 --> 00:36:23.920
When it comes to the WCAG, we have
a text resize that means we have

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:33.790
to be able to resize the text
to 200% but that's actually not

00:36:33.790 --> 00:36:34.860
what our users use.

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:38.240
They use full-screen magnification
sometimes up to eight times,

00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:40.720
and that actually means
that the area they see

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:43.200
if the screen is
really, really small.

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:47.140
Sometimes they use color
filters, color enhancements,

00:36:47.140 --> 00:36:52.640
focus enhancements, that is a big
bright yellow arrow or something.

00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:54.560
Sometimes, they use click to read.

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:58.540
They have many ways
into using a webpage.

00:36:58.540 --> 00:37:00.440
One of the things
that, for instance,

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:02.890
Anna talked about was the
way we designed the black

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:09.150
with yellow text-on, the entrance
for the low vision users.

00:37:11.970 --> 00:37:15.610
When you use color enhancements,
not inverse colors,

00:37:15.610 --> 00:37:18.360
but reverse colors,
I think it's called in zoom text,

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:21.650
you would get the black to be white,
but the yellow keeps being yellow.

00:37:21.650 --> 00:37:25.520
That means the contrast was horrible
and is horrible, but it is one

00:37:25.520 --> 00:37:30.960
of the things that actually
is hard to do something about.

00:37:30.960 --> 00:37:34.280
That is an editorial thing that
we have to figure out how we want

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:36.690
to do that.

00:37:36.690 --> 00:37:40.950
Low vision users, colors, and
magnifications are actually something

00:37:40.950 --> 00:37:45.680
that's even harder when you ask
me than screen reader users.

00:37:48.250 --> 00:37:49.810
What have we learned?

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:53.450
We have to start from the
beginning and choose wisely.

00:37:53.450 --> 00:37:56.220
The fundamentals are hard to
change once we have started.

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:02.179
It is very, very, very excellent

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:04.580
if you could have an
accessibility expert

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:09.520
at your side because no matter how
good you think the bureau you have

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:11.700
at your side is,
they're not that great.

00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:15.580
That's a key point.

00:38:16.640 --> 00:38:19.820
One of the other key points
is content is actually

00:38:19.820 --> 00:38:21.630
the most important thing.

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:24.840
It's not the technical
stuff, it is the content.

00:38:24.840 --> 00:38:29.040
When the solution is done,
when you are more or less secure

00:38:29.040 --> 00:38:32.980
in the accessibility of the
platform, you have to be aware

00:38:32.980 --> 00:38:37.570
that the content editors will be
able to screw this up, train them.

00:38:37.570 --> 00:38:39.930
Have a starting point, a
plan, and work from there.

00:38:39.930 --> 00:38:41.470
Accessibility is a project.

00:38:41.470 --> 00:38:45.080
We're not there yet,
but we have to keep going,

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:47.200
but there will never
be a finishing line.

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:48.520
There will be new standards.

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:53.270
There will be new excessive
technologies and so on and so on.

00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:56.120
As Anna has done, test, test, test.

00:38:56.120 --> 00:39:00.590
The people we have doing testing
with us are actually our goal.

00:39:00.590 --> 00:39:03.600
